Software Requirements 

Introduction
Software Requirements describe what a software system should do and how it should perform. They clearly define the needs and expectations of users, clients, and stakeholders before development begins.
Software requirements act as a foundation for the entire Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) because development, testing, and deployment are all based on these requirements.
If requirements are unclear or incorrect, the final software may fail even if it has no technical defects.

What are Software Requirements?
Software requirements are a detailed description of:

System features
Functional behavior
Performance expectations
Constraints and conditions
They help developers understand what to build and help testers understand what to test.

Types of Software Requirements

Software requirements are mainly divided into two categories:

1. Functional Requirements
Definition
Functional requirements describe what the system should do. They define system features, functions, and operations.
Examples
User should be able to register.
User login with username and password.
Add products to cart.
Make online payment.
Generate reports.

Characteristics
Describe system actions.
Directly related to business logic.
Can be verified using test cases.

Example (E-commerce Website)
User can search products.
User can place orders.
Admin can manage inventory.

2. Non-Functional Requirements
Definition
Non-functional requirements describe how the system should perform rather than what it does.
They focus on quality attributes of the software.

Types with Examples
Type	                    Example
Performance	     Page loads within 2 seconds
Security	      User data must be encrypted
Usability	       Easy navigation interface
Reliability	    System available 99.9% time
Scalability   	Supports 10,000 users simultaneously
Compatibility	     Works on mobile and desktop
Importance      Non-functional requirements improve user experience and system efficiency.

Requirement Documents
Requirements are documented formally so all teams understand them clearly.

1. BRD (Business Requirement Document)
Prepared by Business Analysts.
Contains business goals and customer needs.
Written in simple business language.

Example:
Customer wants an online food ordering system.

2. SRS (Software Requirement Specification)
Detailed technical document.
Used by developers and testers.
Contains functional and non-functional requirements.
Includes:
   System features
   User interfaces
   Constraints
   Performance requirements
   Requirement Gathering Process

The process of collecting requirements includes:
Requirement Elicitation
        Gathering requirements from stakeholders through meetings and discussions.
Requirement Analysis
        Understanding and refining requirements.
Requirement Documentation
        Writing requirements in BRD/SRS.
Requirement Validation
        Confirming requirements with stakeholders.
Requirement Management
        Handling requirement changes.

Characteristics of Good Requirements
 Good software requirements should be:
              Clear – Easy to understand.
              Complete – Covers all functionalities.
              Consistent – No contradictions.
              Testable – Can be verified using test cases.
              Feasible – Possible to implement.

Importance of Software Requirements in Testing
         For testers, requirements are very important because they help to:
Create test scenarios.
Design test cases.
Understand expected results.
Validate system functionality.
Ensure product meets user needs.
Without proper requirements, testing cannot be performed effectively.

Example Scenario
Banking Application Requirement
Functional Requirement
User can transfer money.
Non-Functional Requirement
Transaction should complete within 3 seconds.
System must ensure secure authentication.
Tester will create test cases based on these requirements.

Software requirements are the backbone of software development and testing. 
Clear and well-defined requirements help teams build the correct product, reduce defects, save cost, and improve software quality. 
Proper requirement documentation ensures smooth communication between stakeholders, developers, and testers.
